Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now the Trump White House is taking on the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
Americans value it as much as any other - hence the carefully orchestrated overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad&#39;s Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump regime&#39;s key ideologues, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a token ax to the Statue of Liberty amid a heated argument with CNN&#39;s Jim Acosta over the president&#39;s proposals to drastically curb legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller did not attack the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had done it.
But he attacked its meaning, and particularly the meaning attributed to it when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument&#39;s completion.
As Miller berated Acosta, &quot;I don&#39;t want to go into a whole thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is... a symbol of American liberty that lights up the world.
The poem you are referring to, which was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty.&quot;
Miller is factually correct, but as he himself put it, it&#39;s not really about history.
It&#39;s about the contemporary resonance of the rousing words of Lazarus, the only ones in which a state invites not just any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: &quot;Your weary, your poor, / your oppressed masses who yearn to breathe freely / the wretched refuse of your rich shores.&quot;
There has never been a time when the &quot;miserable waste&quot; on our screens has been more visible.
Miller didn&#39;t engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump&#39;s United States.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural struggle: it is indeed a conflict about the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends, who worked to get her words out on the grassroots after her death - knew very well that they were performing a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the links between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of liberty in a worn classic pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: in her poem the female figure is no longer abstract - she has been given a voice.
And she gives herself a completely different name: Mother of the Exiles.
The pairing of the poem with the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating assault on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right wing people have long wanted to change it back.
Big shouter Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty is inviting no one but rather an early neocon bringing the American flame to the bedraggled world: &quot;Lady Liberty is leading.
She is to carry the torch of liberty from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not intended to light the way to the United States.&quot;
Quite unusually, Limbaugh stumbled upon something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of perspective.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see her as she was seen on the decks of ships by the weary, wretched, but hopeful people after long and often horrific journeys.
It&#39;s literally about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking sanctuary and a chance to improve their lives.
Her statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that, of course, isn&#39;t the perspective Miller and Trump ever want to acknowledge.
Her torch is not meant to light the way, but to ignite the hatred that is her only source of power.
