Blocking Critics via Facebook: Don&#39;t run for public office if you can&#39;t stand voter-bashing
The father of our country knew about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn&#39;t long before the newspapers slammed him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
He scolded the criticism, sure.
But he has not silenced his critics.
For in 1783 Washington said: &quot;Freedom of speech can be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we shall be led like sheep to the slaughter.&quot;
This brings me to Maryland to see Governor Larry Hogan who needs to work to be more like Washington.
Hogan&#39;s staff have blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who have expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him over it earlier this week.
The governor&#39;s staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online comment was rife with a &quot;So what?&quot; backlash. .
&quot;It&#39;s just Facebook,&quot; many people said.
But it&#39;s important.
And it&#39;s especially important when it&#39;s a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly democratic state who is amazingly popular.
He has the second-highest approval rating of the nation&#39;s 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in running his state and strict adherence to principles.
He was also very adept at using Facebook as his primary means of connecting with his constituents and easily debuting his hairless head after chemotherapy on his side.
Therefore, blocking people from coming to the governor&#39;s side — which is a public forum pretended to be official and employees paid in public tax dollars — is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan&#39;s spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor&#39;s actions, arguing that blocking the comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it&#39;s too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people wielding the whip online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people speaking to their chosen leaders: a teacher, an entrepreneur and a minister, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful, and not profane.
The minister quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan&#39;s Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md. was not hateful, but did ask about hate crimes.
&quot;I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other breaking news,&quot; she wrote in the comments section of The Post news show.
&quot;I don&#39;t like that idea either, if a number of people take a stand on the same issue then some tend to disregard it as a so-called collective effort rather than a large group of concerned citizens.&quot;
What the governor&#39;s staff called a &quot;concentrated spam attack&quot; others would likely call &quot;advocacy.&quot;
The Facebook era makes it easy to tailor a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It&#39;s a lot cleaner than in the past if you had done the same thing, dispatched staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or arrest and silence protesters.
But that&#39;s exactly what&#39;s happening digitally right now.
Hogan isn&#39;t the first public official to be criticized for berating Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones on this issue fell in Virginia last week.
The chairman of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to US District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a voter from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Gov. Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
That shouldn&#39;t be that difficult.
In Washington&#39;s time, the era of affordable postage had a similar impact to the Internet.
The number of newspapers multiplied between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter writers lashed out at its leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
The people using pseudonyms like &quot;Juricola,&quot; &quot;Valerius,&quot; &quot;Belisarius,&quot; and &quot;Portius&quot; all wrote letters to newspapers beating down Washington&#39;s decisions.
Petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Amity, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Project&#39;s Online Papers.
But he didn&#39;t shut her up.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are fundamental to our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
