Poverty and Death in the Indonesian Land of Gold
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn&#39;t use a stove.
In fact, she rarely uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of the Paniai Regency in the troubled Indonesian province of Papua, the housewife usually puts a sweet potato - known locally as a &quot;nota&quot; - right in the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and devoured with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the dirt floor - she has no furniture - where she also carries out her daily work, e.g. B. washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband&#39;s four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: most of the village men are unemployed and many drink heavily, and there are the soldiers here.
&quot;Nobody dares walk around the village after 5 p.m.,&quot; she says.
It&#39;s a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony, recorded in Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum when just 1,026 elders were to vote by public census before occupying forces.
An existing pro-independence movement against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control of the region and bars foreign journalists or legal observers.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent part of Papua New Guinea covering the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate. The trip includes a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital of Jayapura to Nabire and then a 5-hour morning drive by rental car.
There is no public transport.
The town of about 19,000 is made up of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated iron roofs that have been rusted to various hues of tawny.
Very few Indonesians have made their journey here, let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
There were other changes too.
&quot;We weren&#39;t used to wearing those clothes,&quot; Degei says, hinting at her vibrant, handwoven turban, dark shirt, and light-colored skirt.
&quot;We used to only have leaves on our bodies.&quot;
Papua is Indonesia&#39;s poorest province, where 28% of the people live below the poverty line and has some of the worst child mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia&#39;s gold country.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of Phoenix, is just 60 miles from Paniai, a New Jersey-sized upland province with a population of 153,000.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources valued at an estimated US$78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of misery for the Papuans, ensuring Indonesia&#39;s powerful military maintains a stifling presence.
A 2005 investigation in The New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including up to $150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are being treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua&#39;s tribal highlands in the 1970s became genocide according to the Asia Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, the Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful demonstrators last year.
&quot;We Will Lose Everything,&quot; says a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which includes reports of atrocities from the previous year, including unlawful executions and torture - rape and electrocution being particularly popular according to another report - and the brutal repression of peaceful demonstrations.
&quot;It&#39;s difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week,&quot; said Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have intensified as Papua&#39;s resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province&#39;s population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people struggle to keep up here.
&quot;Migrants have started selling chickens and vegetables at the traditional market cheaper than local Papuans,&quot; explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai local who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura to work.
&quot;It has cost the native Papuans — the mama-mama [the women] of Papua — their market.&quot;
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, pledged to address inequalities and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua&#39;s 29 districts - including Paniai - on the way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today locals feel betrayed.
&quot;Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 with the expectation that he will fulfill our hopes for justice to be restored,&quot; You says.
In fact, Paniai hit rock bottom just two months after Jokowi&#39;s inauguration in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols in front of a bonfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers burst through the darkness on a motorbike.
The frightened children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offense at her tone and later came back with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers, who had been drinking, chased and hit the group with their rifle butts, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so severely that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby Government Commission building was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at a soccer field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - walking in circles and imitating a bird song - by Papua&#39;s Mee Pago tribe.
Some demonstrators began throwing stones at police and military posts.
When the atmosphere heated up, an order was sent to the soldiers over an internal radio: &quot;If the masses resist more than three times, shoot them dead,&quot; according to an official TIME document, which has not been released to local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of Enarotali&#39;s Kego Koto district, saw the looming danger and called for calm, urging the crowd to return home.
Nobody was in the mood to listen.
&quot;As I turned around, I suddenly got shot in my left wrist,&quot; he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn&#39;t know who fired, but says the bullet came from among the soldiers gathered here.
&quot;It was crowded, many shots were fired,&quot; he adds.
Local man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin who witnessed the shootings.
&quot;I ran to him and checked his body to make sure it was him,&quot; said Yohanes, who, like many Indonesians, has only one name, told TIME in a somber mood.
&quot;I saw that he was dead... I kissed him.&quot;
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers only wanted to &quot;secure&quot; their station because it was under attack.
&quot;We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us,&quot; Papuan police spokesman Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
&quot;It&#39;s about life and death.&quot;
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many others injured.
News of the killings was filtered to Jakarta the following day.
For three weeks, Jokowi delivered an impassioned speech in Jayapura, expressing sympathy for the victims&#39; families and vowing to address historical grievances in Papua.
&quot;I want this case to be solved immediately so that it doesn&#39;t happen again in the future,&quot; he said.
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he was establishing an out-of-court mechanism to resolve historic human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
&quot;Most of the injuries happened a long time ago.
Some were in the 90&#39;s and early 2000&#39;s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but there are processes that need to be followed,&quot; he said.
Then Wiranto retreated when he spoke to TIME in Jakarta on June 5 and said he had no plans to set up a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, &quot;everything will be regulated by law,&quot; he said.
Wiranto, whom the UN has indicted for &quot;crimes against humanity&quot; that left more than 1,000 dead in East Timor&#39;s bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights abuses in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
Families of the Paniai victims met such claims with grim disbelief.
&quot;I&#39;ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there hasn&#39;t been any progress,&quot; says Yohanes.
&quot;I am tired.&quot;
He says years later he still lives in fear.
&quot;I&#39;m scared,&quot; he says.
&quot;I&#39;m afraid of being arrested by the military, afraid of being shot.&quot;
His brother Yacobus reiterated the view that the people of Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the military after helping bury four of the victims.
&quot;After I buried the bodies, the military came looking for me,&quot; he says.
The shootings haven&#39;t stopped.
