One person died and 17 others were injured, including children, during a confrontation between villagers and the manager of a construction company, which refused to take an unconscious man to hospital.
The man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to hospital.
Excited villagers protested outside the company&#39;s on-site office.
Police said villagers threw stones at officers, who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) started shooting at the crowd, killing one.
&quot;We were so panicked, we&#39;re afraid there will be revenge,&quot; said 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed how the injured were quickly admitted here, according to TIME.
&quot;I hid in my house for two days.&quot;
The Deiyai Parliament has called for the officers involved to be held accountable and for the police mobile brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a trouble spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development fuels the dissatisfaction of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribesmen living in Papua&#39;s verdant highlands.
Many have joined the Free Papuan Movement (OPM), the rebel army that claims to be defending Papuans&#39; rights by instigating sporadic attacks and kidnappings of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders hail from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained in Paniai in recent years under the pretense of &quot;securing national sovereignty&quot;.
Some never show up again.
Paniai is known among the people of Papua as &quot;a tragic, forgotten place&quot;.
Poverty increases dissatisfaction.
