New results of the Swedish asylum age assessment tests published
The latest results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, who underwent a new method of medically assessing their age, show that more than 80 percent of those tested are older than 18 years. But not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Board of Forensic Medicine (Rättsmedicinalverket) started conducting the tests last year.
They are said to make age assessments more accurate during the asylum process after the Swedish Migration Board (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to assess the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were judged to be 18 or older, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged that the person was &quot;possibly 18 years of age or older&quot;.
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person &quot;may be under the age of 18&quot;.
The tests are only carried out in cases where the person&#39;s age is in question.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
&quot;We don&#39;t see a big difference in the statistics over the past few months, the numbers are pretty consistent,&quot; he told The Local magazine.
The high proportion of cases where the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker lied about their age.
In May, the agency released the results of 581 tests, saying there were 442 cases that &quot;suggested that the person tested was 18 years of age or older.&quot;
