NHS (National Health Service) to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be able to access &quot;transformative&quot; HIV prevention treatment from September after a High Court battle against funding for the drug in the NHS.
NHS England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken before sexual intercourse, which can reduce the risk of infection in high-risk patients by around 86 per cent, is now being delivered by the health service via an initial three-year study involving an estimated 10,000 people.
He agreed to fund the process after the Court of Appeal upheld a Supreme Court ruling last year that gave the NHS the power to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed as an &quot;important new intervention&quot; by NHS England boss Simon Stevens, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a &quot;defining moment&quot;.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to enroll, with more clinics to follow in October before rolling out across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a sequence of HIV supplements taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that there are just enough drugs in a person&#39;s body to prevent HIV infection.
Such drugs can be taken as little as two hours before intercourse every day or so.
Those who are eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, trans people, and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinicians will identify eligible participants who will consent to the study, including males, females, transgender people and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People living in England who are registered with a GP can also sign up for possible participation at their local participating sex clinic.
The scheme is worth £10million and NHS England signed a deal to supply the drugs this week after an international competitive sourcing.
The study is designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is being targeted, taken up and implemented at scale.
Stevens said: &quot;This major new intervention should complement and overtake the far-reaching and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity&#39;s greatest public health challenges.&quot;
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National AIDS Trust), said: &quot;This is a pivotal moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted to those in need and at risk, offers the opportunity to transform the UK HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, which will improve many, many lives leads.
We warmly welcome this announcement.&quot;
Ian Green, Chief Executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: &quot;The priority now must be to ensure that the study is rapidly rolled out across the country and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that the PrEP test medicine has been obtained, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people living with HIV.&quot;
Sharon Hodgson, shadow health secretary, said: &quot;After months of delays and hesitant government implementation, the start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and end transmission of this life-changing infection.
