Mordillo&#39;s bulbous noses and laughter against suffering
At one point, Mordillo was one of the most widely published cartoon artists, and his characters&#39; bulbous noses are his trademark.
Even at 85, the Argentinean is still drawing and working on a film.
His message: laughter, &quot;because there is too much suffering in the world&quot;.
Guillermo Mordillo was born on August 4, 1932 to Spanish immigrants in Buenos Aires.
In the early years as an artist, he struggled through, among other things, as a draftsman for greeting cards - which frustrated him.
&quot;The happiest day of my professional life was the day I lost my job,&quot; he once said.
After working in Lima, New York and Paris, he made his breakthrough at the end of the 1960s with the publication of his cartoons in &quot;Paris Match&quot; and then also in &quot;Stern&quot; and other leading magazines around the world.
Even in China, Mordillo found many fans.
The artist was repeatedly inspired by cities.
Large, plump Mordillo figures cavort in drawings with the Leaning Tower of Pisa, Big Ben in London and Red Square in Moscow.
According to his own statements, he still sits at the drawing table early in the morning and works almost ten hours a day.
His droll figures continue to be widely distributed around the world in the form of calendars, puzzles, books for young and old, T-shirts, stuffed animals and watches.
He has also been working on an animated film and a TV series with his characters for the past six years.
The main character in the film &quot;Crazy Island&quot; is a giraffe - Mordillo&#39;s favorite animal in his drawings - who has a centipede as an opponent.
His characters speak for the first time in the 3D film, which is due to hit cinema screens in 2019.
&quot;I don&#39;t know exactly what they&#39;re going to say, it&#39;s strange to me,&quot; says Mordillo.
The screenplay is not written by him.
That&#39;s why he prefers the TV series, which, like his original drawings, is produced wordlessly.
Lavender from Provence threatened by climate change
It&#39;s become a symbol of Provence in southern France, but there&#39;s a warning it&#39;s threatened by climate change.
Lavender is in decline because of drought-like conditions and disease-carrying insects, causing major headaches for scientists and farmers trying to find solutions.
Eric Chaisse, expert from the agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence, said: &quot;The lavender in Provence is effectively endangered because in recent years the plant has been exposed to the effects of climate change, which has brought much less rain in spring and much more in autumn .
This affects the lifespan of lavender.
There&#39;s also a small cicada, a microbacterium that transmits leafhoppers, and in very dry weather there&#39;s a lot of them.&quot;
And the stakes are high.
Lavender oil not only attracts holidaymakers, it is also in great demand for perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: &quot;Instead of having very long plant ears with large numbers of flowers, we have smaller, underdeveloped, and either absent or weakened.
So we have fewer essential oil parts.&quot;
Solutions being considered include better water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, but also spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and developing cultivars that are more drought-resistant.
