The murder of a journalist underscores the growing threat in Mexico
Staffers at the weekly Riodoce usually meet on Wednesdays to review their plans for reporting on Sinaloa State&#39;s recent chaos at the hands of organized crime, corrupt officials and incessant drug wars.
But that day, in the shadow of their own tragedy, they came together to talk about safety.
They have been told that it is important to change their routines.
Two senior journalists discuss what feels safer: bring their children, who were the target of a grenade attack in 2009, to the office or leave them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a plaque at the front of the room: Enemies, Neutrals, Allies.
They ask reporters to suggest names for each column - no proof is needed, perceptions and gut feelings are enough.
There are drug smugglers, politicians, businessmen, journalists suspected of being on government or cartel payrolls, a catalog of criminals who make the chaos of Mexico dangerous.
There is no respite from the violence, and as bodies pile up across the country, more and more journalists have joined the ranks: at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012. 589 are under federal protection after attacks and threats and so far this year there have been at least seven deaths in seven states.
Among the latter is its editor and inspiration of Riodoce, the co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
&quot;The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist,&quot; Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violence.
His absence is deeply felt, although his presence is everywhere - a large photo of Valdez showing his middle finger with the word &quot;Justice&quot; hangs on the facade of the Riodoce building. Two reporters in their thirties, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts showing his smiling face with glasses or his signature Panama hat.
The workshop takes place less than two months after his death and the reporters discuss their common issues, the trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor&#39;s office was established in 2010 to handle journalists&#39; cases, it has only initiated two criminal cases, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders linked to drug trafficking and organized crime each year, journalists rarely bring the killers to justice.
At Riodoce, they still insist on covering the violence of Sinaloa, heartbroken and even though the terrain is now even more treacherous.
Without information about the killers, without justice, the meeting to discuss security is of little use, Ibarra says.
&quot;It&#39;s very foolish to waste my time in this workshop,&quot; he says.
&quot;Until we know why, we distrust everyone.&quot;
On the morning of May 15, Valdez left the offices of the Riodoce newspaper in the state capital of Culiacan.
He only managed to drive a few blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was pulled over by two men. He was forced out of his car and shot 12 times, presumably because of the newspaper&#39;s name - which translates to &quot;Twelfth River&quot;.
The gunman drove away in his car and damaged it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He left a wife and two adult children.
Rumors tend to fly loose in Culiacan.
But on the subject of Valdez, there is practically nothing but silence.
Since Guzman&#39;s arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa had become one of the country&#39;s bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions struggle to fill the vacuum.
It doesn&#39;t matter that every day in Sinaloa someone or more people are shot in the street or that the cemetery is full of ornate, two-story mausoleums for drug kingpins that are larger than many houses for the living.
Forget for a minute that there is a state of &quot;quiet&quot; when only one cartel is in control of the coastal state with its valuable ports and drug trafficking routes to the United States.
Despite this, and despite the fact that Valdez was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez, 60, a co-founder and director of Riodoce, has broken with the guilt of failing to protect his friend.
He believes two misunderstandings contributed to the murder.
First there was the publication in February of an interview with Damaso Lopez, a leader of one of the rival cartel factions at war with Guzman&#39;s sons.
This publication may have angered the Sons, with suspected gang members buying up every copy of the issue as soon as it was delivered to newsstands.
The second mistake was failing to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety following the seizure of another newspaper that had published the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is seen as a milestone in Mexico&#39;s violence against journalists.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be around.
He was a veteran reporter for Noroeste in 2003 when he teamed up with five colleagues to found Riodoce and sold $50 equity interests.
In Sinaloa, &quot;it was impossible to do journalism without running into the drug problem,&quot; Bojorquez said.
Over time, the newspaper earned a reputation for bold and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters loved being able to publish hard-hitting investigations without fear of censorship, and readers were fascinated by a publication where they could read stories no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after Riodoce was founded, she received the prestigious &quot;Maria Moors Cabot Prize&quot; for her reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the Committee to Protect Journalists&#39; International Press Freedom Award for his courage in pursuing Mexico&#39;s drug history, wherever it led.
He freely admitted that he was scared.
&quot;I want to live on,&quot; he said at the time of the CPJ awards.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa &quot;is a way of life,&quot; he said in an interview with Rompeviento-TV last October.
&quot;You have to take on the job that falls to you as a journalist - either that or play the fool.
I don&#39;t want to be asked, &quot;With so many dead, what did you do...why didn&#39;t you say what was going on?&quot;
The Riodoce team misses Valdez, the joker who could swear like a docker, the friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They trusted his routine.
He would always wear his hat.
He would always go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and always sit at the same table.
Now they ask: Was his love of routine his undoing?
His death has also forced them to question their own assumptions about how best to do their jobs while staying alive.
&quot;They don&#39;t like it when you deal with their wives, their children, their clean businesses, their clandestine runways&quot; to move drugs.
&quot;These things were not allowed,&quot; Bojorquez said.
The result, even at the best of times, is a high level of self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trust your own instincts.
If it smells wrong, stay away from it.
The trouble is, said the editor of the Riodoce Andres Villarreal, that &quot;smell is a sense that can be fooled... and then the thing with Javier happened.&quot;
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - just as they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt government officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
Cell phones were suddenly not allowed in the room where Riodoce employees met for safety training. Days earlier, it was revealed that spyware, sold exclusively to governments, was being used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
Outside, two police officers took shelter from the 104 degrees (40C) heat under the shade of a tree.
They were hired by the state government to protect Riodoce&#39;s offices in a four-story building in a middle-class neighborhood of Culiacan.
Half-jokingly, some of the reporters wondered if these officers belonged to the 50 percent of police officers whom the governor himself described as untrustworthy.
It&#39;s been months since reporters went to the mountainous terrain where the drug gangs are under de facto control.
For this week&#39;s edition, Riodoce has looked at three main stories.
There was the murder of the brother of former popular boxer Julio Cesar Chavez in Sinaloa.
They also had a government spending exposé that focused on the governor&#39;s hometown.
And there was a group that carried out a kidnapping at one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block from the DA&#39;s office.
There was no official word on who was kidnapped or how it happened, so caution was advised when it came time to write what everyone in town knows: that the restaurant is a favorite haunt of drug dealers and authorities.
A reporter learned from public records that the restaurant was registered under the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of politics for most of the century.
Recently, several PRI governors have been accused of high-profile cases of corruption.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents at the venue, including one in which a son of &quot;El Chapo&quot; Guzman escaped a military ambush.
Just months earlier, readers would have viewed Valdez&#39;s column as the most informed source on the kidnapping.
&quot;We would have known what happened earlier,&quot; said Villarreal, 46, nicknamed &quot;El Flaco&quot; for his slim build.
&quot;Now all channels of communication with our sources are broken.&quot;
Valdez&#39;s office has been repurposed as a repository for signs and stickers protesting the killings of journalists because staff have become what they themselves never expected: activists on behalf of the press.
Reporter Miriam Ramirez grabbed a few signs and went to the prosecutor&#39;s office the next morning to protest over another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared in western Michoacan state three days after Valdez was killed.
A burned body was discovered and officials say it is his based on DNA testing.
Across the country, journalists have become more vocal, writing &quot;SOS Press&quot; on sidewalks and structures in organized protests.
On this day, director Bojorquez is away in Washington trying to rally international support for justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez&#39;s assassination, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and having them killed for telling the truth.
She has since asked to be reassigned by the government because she is concerned her anger violated her objectivity.
Valdez has repeatedly said that journalists in Mexico are &quot;surrounded&quot; by organized crime, government officials involved and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not only killed by drug gangs, but also on orders from politicians and security forces who are in league with organized crime.
The media watchdog group Articulo 19 attributed more than half of the attacks on journalists to police and officials last year.
&quot;In Mexico you die because they want you to shut up,&quot; Ramirez said.
Apparently the murders have a deterrent effect.
No one forgets the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias six years ago in the northern border state of Tamaulipas.
Her body was found along with a note said to be signed by the Zetas Cartel: &quot;Here I am for my reports.&quot;
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some outlets have chosen to close, like the newspaper El Norte in the northern border state of Chihuahua following the March assassination of correspondent Miroslava Breach.
Others are carrying on, as did Nuevo Laredo&#39;s El Manana after the assassination of their director in 2004.
In 2010, the Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly targeted the drug cartels with a front-page editorial headlined &quot;What do you want from us?&quot;
Some journalists have fled their home states or even the country.
It&#39;s a painful decision.
It&#39;s hard to find work in exile and they still watch the streets, looking for danger.
And sometimes they are hunted, as is apparently the case with photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in a Mexico City apartment three months after fleeing Veracruz.
For those who stay behind and continue the work, it&#39;s a daily dance of risky decisions.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits the drug trade terrifies him.
&quot;Mexico is going to hell and that&#39;s why I became a reporter,&quot; he said.
At midnight last Friday, when the last issue had already ended, the editors of Riodoce were sitting on the sidewalk in front of the office drinking beer when all of a sudden their phones started buzzing.
A series of shootings involving gang rivals and security forces near the seaside resort of Mazatlan had left 19 confirmed dead.
The war continued to escalate, as promised by a series of cartel embassies in the region.
From the curb, they published the news on Riodoce&#39;s website via mobile phone.
The front page had to be changed the next day.
Sirens wailed nearby - another gun battle in the area.
Bojorquez glanced at the officers standing guard to see if they were on standby.
If they were afraid at all, they didn&#39;t show it.
Under the massive portrait of the newspaper&#39;s fallen founder, whose middle finger was visible to all of Sinaloa, Riodoce staff followed in his footsteps.
&quot;How can you even consider closing,&quot; Bojorquez said, &quot;when on the same day that Javier was murdered, the intern asked me to put her out on the street to report.&quot;
Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid its enemies
At first glance it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Now researchers have found that the first glimpses of a Canadian miner&#39;s incredible rhinoceros were so well preserved that experts have described it as the &#39;Mona Lisa of the dinosaurs&#39;.
It was so well preserved that they could even tell its scaly skin was a reddish brown - and they said it had something of a &quot;troubled past&quot;.
The report in Current Biology called it &quot;the best preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the finest specimens of dinosaur in the world.&quot;
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaurus that lived in the mid-Cretaceous period, between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has stunned researchers, who describe it as &quot;truly remarkable&quot;.
According to reports in National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk while digging at the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
He encountered something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
They spent the next six years trying to uncover the wild beast within the 2,500 pound (1,100 kg) clod of earth.
After all this hard work, the finished result is now ready to be unveiled.
&quot;If you blink your eyes just a little bit, you could almost believe it was asleep,&quot; said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
&quot;It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved specimens of dinosaurs - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.&quot;
Researchers have found that although this herbivore is covered in armor and resembles a walking tank, it was likely threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and employed a shielding technique known as counter-shading, also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend in better with its surroundings and avoid its enemies, experts say, suggesting it may have been threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature of the nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal, naming it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team that spent more than 7,000 hours painstakingly uncovering it.
The astonishing preservation of the specimen enabled Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armor over his body.
They discovered countershading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, meaning the creature&#39;s top was darker than its underside.
Although countershading is common, the results are surprising, as Borealopelta&#39;s size far exceeds that of animals alive today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was hunted by enough pressure from carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favored the disguise of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most contemporary animals that employ countershading—think deer, zebra, or armadillo—are much smaller and more vulnerable than prey, signaling that this nodosaur faced a real struggle for survival.
&quot;Strong predatory behavior on a massive, heavily armored dinosaur shows just how dangerous Cretaceous dinosaur predators must have been,&quot; Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in their scales also shows that the dinosaur&#39;s skin was reddish-brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved gut contents, to find out what it ate for its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it got caught in a river and was swept out to sea, where it sank on its back to the sea floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans were probably much further inland than they are today.
&quot;This nodosaurus is really remarkable because it&#39;s completely covered in preserved scaly skin, but it&#39;s also preserved in three dimensions and retains the animal&#39;s original shape,&quot; Brown said.
&quot;The result is that the animal looks almost the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don&#39;t need to use much imagination to reconstruct it. If you squint your eyes just a little bit, you could almost believe he&#39;s asleep.&quot;
The Cretaceous Period was a time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that stood on two legs, roamed the earth.
Although their king, the Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armored dinosaur was hunted by some of its fearsome ancestors.
These include the Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot (11.5 m) long, six-ton monster.
The scientists, whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology, believe that Borealopelta sank under the sea and became mummified in the mud after it died.
The creature was found by Shawn Funk while digging at the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada on March 21, 2011.
According to the museum, it&#39;s the best preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including skin and armor, and is complete from snout to rump.
The creatures averaged about 18 feet (5 meters) in length and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
It contained two 20-inch spikes protruding from his shoulders.
Researchers believe the armored herbivore swept through western Canada until a flooded river swept it out to sea.
But the dinosaur&#39;s underwater burial preserved its armor in exquisite detail.
The fossilized remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the remains of skin still cover bumpy armor plates along the length of the dinosaur
As Michael Greshko has written for National Geographic, such a level of conservation is as &#39;rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more confusing it gets.
Petrified remains of skin still cover the bumpy armor plates that support the animal&#39;s skull.
His right front foot is at his side, his five fingers are spread upwards.
I can count the scales on its sole&#39;.
