Deutsche Bahn: Group tests &quot;comfort check-in&quot;
It&#39;s a moment that almost everyone has experienced at least once: You sit on the train and sleep, not suspecting anything.
Or you are engrossed in your work and just have a brilliant idea.
And then: puff.
The conductor comes and wakes you up roughly or pulls the passenger out of the workflow.
ticket control.
But the days of interruptions will soon be over.
Deutsche Bahn is currently testing conductorless ticket inspection.
You simply confirm by mobile phone that you have taken your seat and thereby validate the ticket.
Test operations are currently running on two routes.
&quot;If the offer goes through, we&#39;ll expand it.
It will then probably be available on many other long-distance routes in Germany at the beginning of next year,&quot; said a railway spokesman.
&quot;Comfort check-in&quot; is what Deutsche Bahn calls ticket validation without a conductor.
In order to be able to use it, however, a few requirements must be met: You need a smartphone or tablet.
And you have to have booked an online ticket - which most passengers do anyway.
You also have to have bought it via the Deutsche Bahn app, the DB Navigator, which is the most convenient way to book tickets anyway.
And lastly, you need a seat reservation.
Because &quot;Comfort Check-in&quot; works like this: You get on the train, call up your ticket under &quot;My Tickets&quot;.
A button for electronic validation then appears for the test customers.
The train attendants receive a message on their mobile devices that passenger X is on the train and has taken the booked seat Y.
If the train conductor comes to seat Y during ticket inspection, he knows that a passenger with an already validated online ticket is sitting there.
So you can keep sleeping, keep working, keep silent.
The &quot;check-in&quot; has two advantages: one for the customer, one for the train - which in turn should benefit the passengers.
&quot;Anyone who wants to travel in a relaxed manner without having their tickets checked by our train attendants can simply check in themselves in the DB Navigator.
This enables passengers to personalize their travel time on the train,&quot; says Michael Peterson, Board Member for Marketing at DB Fernverkehr.
Second plus: &quot;And our employees have more time than today to respond to individual customer needs&quot;.
Anyone who often travels by train knows that in addition to delays and missed trains, ticket checks are one of the biggest annoyances.
Because you often do not have all the documents with you that you need to validate online tickets, but in any case one of the passengers does not have them with you.
Either the credit card or the identity card or another document that you have to show is missing.
The consequences are endless discussions between train attendants and passengers, which leads to a bad atmosphere in the compartment or the large area and delays in checking your own tickets, and ultimately takes the time away from the conductor to take care of other matters.
Only a small number of test customers can use the new service.
And that only on the ICE 915 Dortmund-Stuttgart and ICE 912 Stuttgart-Essen connections.
Other train numbers on the same route have not yet been activated.
How one activist came to learn the answer to the question, &quot;Whose Streets?&quot;
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just a day after arriving in New York City, the St. Louis native sat on the bed of an Airbnb she rented and scrolled through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone in high school.
&quot;Police just killed an 18-year-old child and he&#39;s still lying on the street,&quot; it said.
Confused that no one else had posted the information on her feed, she shut down Facebook and opened up on Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis-area rapper was live-tweeting the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old man who was killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown&#39;s lifeless body stretched out on the street and would remain there for four hours.
&quot;That&#39;s wild,&quot; Ferrell thought to himself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put down her phone to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were photos of police tape and people shouting and of a man claiming to be Brown&#39;s father carrying a sign that read, &quot;Ferguson&#39;s police just killed my unarmed son!&quot;
She watched a live feed showing a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer cocked his gun and yelled, &quot;I&#39;m going to kill you... animals all.&quot;
&quot;It&#39;s not common,&quot; Ferrell recalled her statement.
&quot;This is not the kind of murder that we have become accustomed to and can call typical.&quot;
At that moment I felt chills.
I was angry and crying.&quot;
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11pm, she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father&#39;s house and decided the two of them would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, &quot;Whose Streets?&quot;, in theaters May 11.
It&#39;s a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience, set through the eyes of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets demanding answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who was wearing a floral dress and matching crown, the two went over a conversation they&#39;d had countless times before that morning &quot;about the black experience and the black condition.&quot;
&quot;You remember how I taught you when black people need to fight for what they believe in?&quot; she remembered what she said.
&quot;We&#39;re going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn&#39;t right.
I couldn&#39;t take her with me,&quot; Ferrell later said.
&quot;What happened today is a culmination of ... what happened in the past.
She needs to know and see and be raised in it.
She needs to be well developed, not just activism and organization, but knowing the different layers of the black experience and the black constitution and what we need to do to become free, to liberate ourselves.
While I&#39;m fortunate enough to give her an experience where she doesn&#39;t personally experience blatant racism, she is no different than the next black woman child.
I feel like I&#39;d be doing her a disservice by keeping her out of it.&quot;
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a location across from the police department that became a camp area as activists awaited Officer Darren Wilson&#39;s possible non-charge.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who made lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them to protesters.
A new kind of activism for Ferrell slowly began to take shape.
&quot;My activism totally changed after August 9,&quot; she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis was President of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food equity and health inequalities in black communities.
&quot;I had no organizing experience.
It all came.&quot;
Weeks later, during an evening demonstration, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film&#39;s co-directors.
Folayan said she and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to &quot;document&quot; what was happening.
