&quot;What I hope people will take away from this is that our genome doesn&#39;t care about who we are and how open genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is,&quot; said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work, Spurious Memories , can also be seen.
&quot;DNA data can tell so many different stories, so that&#39;s 30 of those stories.&quot;
The final piece in the exhibition, kept in its own room, is a page from the comic novella mentioned above.
It shows Manning emerging from the disciplinary barracks of the United States like King-Kong, speakerphone in hand.
&quot;If they cold your speech, then they&#39;ve won,&quot; they say.
&quot;So never shut up&quot;.
&quot;It came right out of a letter she wrote me,&quot; said the artist, who greets from Philadelphia.
&quot;I still get goosebumps talking about it.&quot;
Manning has yet to see the exhibit in person - as was presciently anticipated in the comic book - but if she does, she will be greeted in the center of the room by the masks, her own genomic simulacra, moving like hordes rally of protesters.
That was also purposeful, as was everything in the exhibit, right down to the height (5&quot; 2, Manning&#39;s stature) at which their genetic haplogroups were penciled.
&quot;In the past I&#39;ve had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd,&quot; said Dewey-Hagborg of the portraits.
