But Scotney has experienced 700 years of tumultuous history from his cozy perch in Kent&#39;s Bewl River valley and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired Yorkshireman with a penchant for historical documents.
&quot;I think it&#39;s so nice to look at the handwriting of someone who&#39;s been dead for 300 years,&quot; he says wistfully.
&quot;What a personal connection to hold this letter in my hand.&quot;
&#39;A Castle in England&#39; spans the period from the Middle Ages to the Edwardian period and documents the families who lived in Scotney. Each story was illustrated by a different emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It&#39;s not Rhodes&#39; first book to be based on an archive: he wrote &#39;Dead Men&#39;s Teeth and Other Stories&#39; in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
&quot;I only reacted that way to the thumbprint on the page of a letter written by a double agent working for the Jacobins in the 1700s,&quot; he says.
