For someone so wrapped up in paperwork that he&#39;s supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England, and lived in a castle for almost four months (&quot;To be honest, I overstated my welcome a little&quot;), that all seems like it to be too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian &#39;new&#39; castle, perusing the archives and studying the castle&#39;s many treasures and curiosities, such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the moat.
He would wander the grounds and ruins of the old castle, speaking to landscapers, gardeners, and sometimes the artists who worked on his book&#39;s illustrations.
Then, at night, he &quot;drank whiskey and started writing&quot;.
Scotney&#39;s intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained full access in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, the staff was just beginning to tend to the archive, which he described as &quot;hundreds of years of aristocrats saying, &#39;Oh, throw it in the attic.&#39;
Diaries, letters from the English Empire period, maps showing who owned what: &quot;You&#39;d think land conflicts would be boring,&quot; says Rhodes, &quot;but there was a birch tree that two families fought over.
