Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a jumping off point to delve into broader English history, including &#39;The Labourer&#39; which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants&#39; Revolt of 1381.
&quot;There is a record of a riot occurring at the castle in 1380 in this book called &#39;Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex,&#39;&quot; says Rhodes.
&quot;The peasant uprising started in this area and I thought an uprising was a good start.
Maybe the two are connected?&quot;
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle&#39;s history - such as &#39;The Priest&#39; which tells the story of the Jesuit Father whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or &#39;The Smuggler&#39;, which portrays 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell staging his own funeral by filling a coffin with rocks (a discovery not made until years later when his coffin was unearthed) .
