Red meat, dairy, and chocolate may help alleviate IBD (Inflammatory Bowel Disease).
Red meat and chocolate can sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study claims just the opposite: A diet high in meat-based proteins and dairy products could reduce symptoms in patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, which affects around 1.3 million in the US and 300,000 in the UK, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurring or bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme tiredness.
While sufferers are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to reduce their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that protein&#39;s essential amino acid, tryptophan, helps develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
The lead researcher, Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells patrol the gut to make sure harmful microbes hiding in food don&#39;t enter the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging delicate tissues.
When the balance tilts too far toward inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can result.
Experiments have found that a type of tolerance-promoting immune cell is present in mice that carry a specific bacterium in their guts.
And the bacterium needs tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to trigger the appearance of the cells.
Professor Colonna said: &quot;We have made a link between a species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the gut microbiome and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more of these immune cells they had.&quot;
He suggested that the combination of L. reuteri and a tryptophan-rich diet promotes more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environments when the same system is at work in humans.
The postdoc Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barragan was studying a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain but housed separately did not.
She suspected the difference had to do with the mice&#39;s gut microbiomes - the community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The mice&#39;s intestines were DNA-sequenced and six types of bacteria were found, which were present in the mice with the immune cells but absent in the mice without them.
Mice were raised in a sterile environment so they lacked a gut microbiome and didn&#39;t develop these types of immune cells, and they received the L. reuteri and the immune cells emerged.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - minus the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells developed into the tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active component was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice&#39;s diet, the number of such cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells fell by half.
dr Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tracts.
It is not known whether tryptophan byproducts from L. reuteri develop cells in humans the way they do in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in humans with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said: &quot;The development of these cells is probably something we want to encourage, as these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the gut.
Potentially, high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri can lead to an expansion of this population.&quot;
