The Connecticut-made helicopter was on display alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House Military Office requested the helicopter&#39;s presence in a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for the operation of the helicopter is responsible.
&quot;I just wanted you to be aware of this because it is such an unusual, high-visibility event,&quot; the commander of the HMX-1 wrote to his superior, the naval deputy commander for aviation, on the eve of the event.
The message indicated that the helicopter arrived at the South Lawn around 7am on July 17 for the 3pm event and stayed until the lawn was cleared between 6pm and 9pm that evening .
The note adds that if departure from the White House were to be delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to duty hour restrictions.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while unit security personnel remained with the aircraft during the time on the ground.
It was not clear from the recordings made available to TIME whether a second flight crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 asked if the event could violate the regulation.
&quot;One question we asked was whether this was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that it was not,&quot; the commander wrote.
&quot;Sounds like you&#39;re closed off,&quot; replied the second-in-command.
The Made in America event was designated an official event by the White House and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the President gave an impetus to the reform of health care reform that was underway in the Senate and touted efforts to curb government regulations.
The use of the aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically advantageous purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But requesting their use only for a photo-op is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane was providing taxi services amid his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Fla., and his Twitter account is full of stories complaining about his predecessor&#39;s use of the presidential plane.
&quot;The White House is excited about the Made In America show -- showcasing products from all 50 states made by American workers with American materials,&quot; said White House Assistant Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights in the Washington area and South Lawn to drop the US President at the White House with precise centimeter readings.
When Trump was in Germany at the G20 summit in early July, HMX-1 performed 58 practice landings in the White House.
The flight for the &quot;Made in America&quot; event counted toward the month&#39;s flight crew training needs, an official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for &quot;non-presidential support missions.&quot;
The White House said taxpayers didn&#39;t shoulder the burden for any of the other props unveiled at the event.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in displaying the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for the Presidential flights and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to the US Department of Defense hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the DoD reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records list the aircraft&#39;s flight time as 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility&#39;s home base at Quantico, Virginia.
The White House argues that the true cost of operating the helicopter is well below that rate.
&quot;Setting the cost to taxpayers based on reimbursement rate estimates is highly misleading,&quot; Walters said.
&quot;These estimates include staff, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual appropriations.&quot;
According to a 2015 RAND study, reimbursement rates for DoD do not include labor costs, but do include fuel, maintenance, and contracting costs.
At the time, former White House Press Secretary Sean Spicer defended the use of the helicopter for the event.
&quot;The idea is to showcase things that are made in America this week,&quot; Spicer said.
&quot;And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut take great pride in contributing to our national security and I understand hundreds if not thousands of people depend on it.
And I think like most Americans, we&#39;re all proud of the helicopter and other military hardware that so many Americans worked tirelessly to create.
It is of course appropriate to point that out.&quot;
It wasn&#39;t clear if Trump was interacting with the helicopter as he entered his tour of the South Lawn for the event, but he did get into the driver&#39;s seat of a fire engine.
At the White House, speaking to Sikorsky officials, Trump joked with the media about his own fleet of company products.
&quot;I know Sikorsky very well,&quot; said the President, &quot;I have three of them.&quot;
